bout 1138":"about 1138","1134":"1134","1166":"1166","about 1166":"about 1166","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rullos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Tullis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tullis","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Fife): probably a habitational name from the lands of Tullois (Fife). The placename appears to be from a Scots plural form of a word borrowed from Gaelic <i>tulach</i> ‘hillock’; compare   Tulloch  ,   Tullie  ."]},{"name":"Tulloss","meanings":["Variant of   Tullos  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":77,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":86,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Rullos was born about 1138, in Clotton, Cheshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert de Rullos."},"et":{"about 1138–":"umbes 1138–Surnud","1134–Male":"1134–Surnud","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","1138–Female":"1138–Surnud","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1224":"1224","about 1138":"umbes 1138","1134":"1134","1166":"1166","about 1166":"umbes 1166","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1138–":"noin 1138–Kuollut","1134–Male":"1134–Kuollut","1166–Female":"1166–Kuollut","1138–Female":"1138–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1224":"1224","about 1138":"noin 1138","1134":"1134","1166":"1166","about 1166":"noin 1166","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1138–":"environ 1138–Décédée","1134–Male":"1134–Décédé","1166–Female":"1166–Décédée","1138–Female":"1138–Décédée","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1224":"1224","about 1138":"environ 1138","1134":"1134","1166":"1166","about 1166":"environ 1166","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, Angleterre","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Rullos est née environ 1138, à Clotton, Cheshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Robert de Rullos."},"de":{"about 1138–":"um 1138–Verstorben","1134–Male":"1134–Verstorben","1166–Female":"1166